    slug: "hisn-ul-muslim-pashto",
    description: `Hisn-ul-Muslim (Pashto) is a Pashto-language edition of the widely celebrated Islamic supplication book "Fortress of the Muslim," originally compiled by Sa'id bin Ali bin Wahf al-Qahtani. This edition brings the comprehensive collection of authentic daily prayers, remembrances (adhkar), and supplications (duas) from the Quran and the Sunnah of Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) to Pashto-speaking Muslims across Afghanistan, Pakistan, and the broader Pashto-speaking diaspora. The book has earned its reputation as one of the most essential everyday references in a Muslim's life because it organizes the Prophetic duas into clearly defined categories covering virtually every situation a person encounters throughout the day, from waking up in the morning and entering the mosque to eating, drinking, traveling, sleeping, and facing times of difficulty or distress.

The book draws its content exclusively from the authentic sources of Islam, including the two Sahih collections of Bukhari and Muslim, the four Sunan works, and other verified hadith compilations. Each dua is presented with its original Arabic text alongside the Pashto translation, enabling readers who may not be fully fluent in Arabic to understand the meaning of every supplication they recite. The inclusion of the Arabic text is particularly important because the duas of the Prophet (peace be upon him) hold a special status when recited in their original form, and having both the Arabic and Pashto available on the same page makes the book accessible to a wide range of readers regardless of their level of Arabic proficiency. The transliteration or clear referencing of each dua helps ensure that readers can pronounce the Arabic correctly even if their formal Arabic education is limited.

The organizational structure of Hisn-ul-Muslim is one of its greatest strengths. The book is divided into thematic sections that correspond to the daily routine and life events of a Muslim. Morning and evening adhkar occupy prominent sections, as these are among the most emphasized acts of worship in the Prophetic tradition. The Prophet (peace be upon him) instructed his companions to recite specific prayers and remembrances every morning and evening as a means of seeking Allah's protection, blessing, and guidance throughout the day and night. Additional sections cover prayers for before and after eating, entering and leaving the home, entering and leaving the mosque, traveling by various means, wearing new clothes, visiting the sick, attending the funeral prayer, and dealing with anxiety, sadness, debt, and other hardships. A dedicated section on seeking refuge from Shaytan, the evil eye, and other harmful forces provides spiritually potent words of protection that every Muslim should have at their disposal. The Pashto translation is clear and faithful to the original meanings, making this edition an invaluable daily companion for Pashto-speaking Muslims of all ages and backgrounds who wish to strengthen their connection with Allah through the authentic supplications of the Prophet.`,
