    slug: "history-of-madinah-munawwarah",
    description: `History of Madinah Munawwarah is an English-language historical reference book that provides a comprehensive account of the city of Madinah, the second holiest city in Islam and the place where Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) established the first Islamic state and where he is buried. The book traces the history of Madinah from its earliest known origins as the settlement of Yathrib, through its transformation into the City of the Prophet (Madinat an-Nabi), and into the modern era, covering the major historical events, the development of its sacred sites, and the evolution of its social, political, and religious significance over more than fourteen centuries. This work serves as an essential reference for anyone interested in the history of the Prophet's city and its central place in Islamic civilization.

The book begins with the pre-Islamic history of Yathrib, describing the city's original inhabitants — the Arab tribes of Aws and Khazraj and the Jewish tribes of Banu Qaynuqa, Banu an-Nadir, and Banu Qurayzah — and the social, political, and economic conditions that characterized the city before the advent of Islam. It covers the events that led to the Prophet's migration (Hijrah) from Makkah to Madinah in 622 CE, which marks the beginning of the Islamic calendar and one of the most pivotal events in human history. The building of the Prophet's Mosque (Masjid an-Nabawi), the establishment of the first Islamic constitution (the Sahifah or Constitution of Madinah), the brotherhood between the Muhajirun (emigrants from Makkah) and the Ansar (helpers from Madinah), and the major battles and treaties of the Prophetic era are all covered in detail.

The book then traces Madinah's history through the era of the Rightly Guided Caliphs, the Umayyad period, the Abbasid period, and subsequent Islamic dynasties, describing how the city developed, the expansions and renovations of the Prophet's Mosque, and the major historical events that took place in Madinah. Special attention is given to the development of the sacred sites in and around Madinah, including Masjid an-Nabawi, Masjid al-Quba (the first mosque in Islam), Masjid al-Qiblatayn (where the direction of prayer was changed from Jerusalem to Makkah), Uhud, the graves of the martyrs of Uhud, and the Baqi cemetery where many of the Prophet's family and companions are buried. The book also covers the modern history of Madinah, including the major expansion projects of the Saudi government that transformed the Prophet's Mosque and the city's infrastructure. Maps, photographs, and illustrations complement the text, making this book a valuable resource for pilgrims, students of Islamic history, and general readers who want to deepen their knowledge of the City of the Prophet.`,
    metaDescription: "History of Madinah Munawwarah traces the holy city from pre-Islamic Yathrib to modern times in English. Covers sacred sites and key historical events."
